{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Carolina", "text_new": "{{short description|Coronavirus disease 2019 pandemic in the U.S. state of South Carolina}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Carolina\n| width           = \n| image           = COVID-19 Warning Mount Pleasant South Carolina.jpg\n| image_size      = 250\n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Warning sign in [[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|Mount Pleasant]]\n| map1            = File:COVID-19 Cases by counties of South Carolina.png\n| legend1         = {{legend|#EC1C24|Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#5C1A27|COVID-19 related deaths}}\n <center>'''''Last updated on April 5, 2020 at 7:45 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]'''''</center>\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[South Carolina]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020<br>[[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston]] and [[Kershaw County, South Carolina|Kershaw]] counties\n| arrival_date    = <!-- or | dates = -->\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 2,049\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 44\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.scdhec.gov/covid19}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[South Carolina]] in March 2020. As of April 5, 2020, the [[South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control]] has confirmed 2,049 cases in the state, resulting in 44 deaths.<ref name=\"DHECcount\">{{cite web |title=Testing & SC Data (COVID-19) {{!}} SCDHEC |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/infectious-diseases/viruses/coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19/testing-sc-data-covid-19 |website=scdhec.gov |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> On April 2, 2020, DHEC announced that the virus had spread to all 46 counties in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 reported in all 46 counties across SC, 4 cases in Laurens County |url=http://www.golaurens.com/news/covid-19-reported-in-all-46-counties-across-sc-4-cases-in-laurens-county/article_49d8a66c-71f9-11ea-9c94-77636b0c19fd.html |website=GoLaurens.Com |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/South Carolina medical cases chart}}\n*'''March 6:''' DHEC announces that two women, one from [[Charleston County, South Carolina|Charleston County]] and one from [[Kershaw County, South Carolina|Kershaw County]], are under investigation and are presumed to have South Carolina's first cases of [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Feit |first1=Noah |last2=Daprile |first2=Lucas |last3=Fretwell |first3=Sammy |title=First potential coronavirus cases under investigation in South Carolina |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/state/south-carolina/article240838221.html |website=thestate.com |publisher=The State |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 7:''' Tests for the two women return as \"presumptive-positive,\" giving South Carolina its first two cases.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Riviera |first1=Ray |last2=Phillips |first2=Patrick |title=First possible S.C. novel coronavirus cases detected in Charleston, Kershaw Counties |url=https://www.live5news.com/2020/03/07/first-possible-novel-coronavirus-cases-detected-charleston-kershaw-counties/ |website=live5news.com |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 12:''' \n**The [[South Carolina Independent School Association]] (SCISA) announces that it will be suspending all athletics until April 3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Glover |first1=Emery |title=SCISA postpones spring sports in S.C. amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/12/scisa-postpones-spring-sports-sc-amid-coronavirus-concerns/ |website=wistv.com |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[South Carolina Science Olympiad]] announces its decision to cancel its state championship tournaments for both divisions.<ref>{{cite web |title=SC SCIENCE OLYMPIAD |url=https://www.sc-so.org/ |website=sc-so.org |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''March 13:''' [[Governor of South Carolina|Governor]] [[Henry McMaster]] declares a [[state of emergency]] and orders the closure of all public schools in Kershaw and [[Lancaster County, South Carolina|Lancaster]] counties for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallory |first1=Laurel |title=S.C. governor declares state of emergency; orders Kershaw, Lancaster county schools to close |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/13/sc-governor-declare-state-emergency-orders-kershaw-lancaster-county-schools-close/ |website=wistv.com |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 15:''' Governor McMaster and other officials announce the closure of all public schools in the state until March 31.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ablon |first1=Matthew |title=SC governor shuts down all public schools until March 31 to combat spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.foxcarolina.com/coronavirus/sc-governor-shuts-down-all-public-schools-until-march-to/article_610dca74-66fa-11ea-a3b1-4b468e5adf2d.html |website=FOX Carolina |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=15 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''March 16:''' \n**A nursing home patient in Lexington County is reported as the first COVID-19 related death in South Carolina.<ref name=\"firstdeath\">{{cite web |title=State of South Carolina Reports First COVID-19 Related Death |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/news-releases/state-south-carolina-reports-first-covid-19-related-death |website=South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallory |first1=Laurel |title=S.C. reports first COVID-19-related death was Lexington Co. nursing home patient |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/16/sc-reports-first-covid-related-death/ |website=wistv.com |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[South Carolina High School League]] (SCHSL) suspends all spring sports until April 5.<ref>{{cite web |title=SCHSL suspends all spring sports due to threat of coronavirus |url=https://www.wmbfnews.com/2020/03/16/schsl-suspends-all-spring-sports-due-threat-coronavirus/ |website=wmbfnews.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 17:''' Governor McMaster issues an executive order requiring the mandatory shutdown of dine-in service in restaurants and bars.  The order also includes the delay of state tax deadlines until June 1, the general request of state agencies to waive any restrictive regulations in order to move faster to address the virus, and also prohibits gatherings of more than 50 people at publicly-owned facilities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order No. 2020-10 |url=https://governor.sc.gov/sites/default/files/Documents/Executive-Orders/2020-03-17%20eFILED%20Executive%20Order%20No.%202020-10%20-%20Directing%20Additional%20Emergency%20Measures%20Due%20to%20COVID-19.pdf |website=South Carolina Office of the Governor |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Governor's Update on Coronavirus (COVID-19) | date=March 17, 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hmFB142WyLw |website=YouTube |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 19:''' The Governor issues an additional executive order, ordering non-essential state employees to stay home, emergency measures for unemployment claims and benefits, among other orders, including calling for all public colleges and universities in the state to finish their semesters online.<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order No. 2020-11 |url=https://governor.sc.gov/sites/default/files/Documents/Executive-Orders/2020-03-19%20FILED%20Executive%20Order%20No.%202020-11%20-%20Additional%20Emergency%20Measures%20%26%20Regulatory%20Relief%20re%20COVID-19.pdf |website=South Carolina Office of the Governor |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Governor's Update on Coronavirus (COVID-19) March 19, 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FH-EOGBEzWI |website=YouTube |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mallory |first1=Laurel |title=S.C. governor asks colleges to complete semester online as 21 more COVID-19 cases reported |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/19/sc-governor-asks-colleges-complete-semester-online-more-covid-cases-reported/ |website=wistv.com |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 20:''' Two deaths are reported, one in Florence County and one in Charleston County, bringing the total for the state to three. Both persons were reported as being elderly and having underlying health conditions.<ref name=\"deaths23\">{{cite web |last1=Mallory |first1=Laurel |title=DHEC: 2 more people in South Carolina die after contracting coronavirus |url=https://www.wistv.com/2020/03/20/dhec-more-people-south-carolina-die-after-contracting-coronavirus/ |website=wistv.com |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 21:''' The Governor says that a [[shelter in place]] is \"not under consideration\" at the time, after rumors to the contrary and similar action being taken by other states.<ref>{{cite web |title=S.C. governor: shelter-in-place \"not under consideration\" |url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/21/sc-governor-shelter-in-place-not-under-consideration/ |website=wbtv.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> McMaster also orders local law enforcement to disperse crowds gathered on state beaches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/21/additional-coronavirus-cases-south-carolina-statewide-total-rises/|title=46 additional coronavirus cases in South Carolina, statewide total rises to 173|last=Staff|first=WBTV Web|website=www.wbtv.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*'''March 23:''' \n**DHEC reports two additional deaths, one from Kershaw County (later reclassified to Sumter County) and one from Clarendon County, bringing South Carolina's total to five. Both persons had underlying health conditions.<ref name=\"deaths45\">{{cite web |title=State of South Carolina Reports Two Additional COVID-19 Related Deaths {{!}} SCDHEC |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/news-releases/state-south-carolina-reports-two-additional-covid-19-related-deaths |website=www.scdhec.gov |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Governor McMaster holds a briefing in which he instructs law enforcement to disperse any public gathering of three or more people, with violations of this rule resulting in a misdemeanor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus updates in SC: Gov. McMaster directs law enforcement to break up public gatherings of 3 or more |url=https://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/news/2020/03/23/coronavirus-updates-sc-heres-what-know-monday-morning/2894988001/ |website=The Greenville News |accessdate=23 March 2020 |language=en |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 24:''' \n**Governor McMaster and State Superintendent of Education Molly Spearman announce that public schools statewide, including colleges and universities, will remain closed through the end of April.<ref>{{cite web |title=SC schools to remain closed through April |url=http://www.golaurens.com/news/sc-schools-to-remain-closed-through-april/article_2deb289e-6e02-11ea-a60b-abceb632d77b.html |website=GoLaurens.Com |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=South Carolina schools will remain closed until the end of April, governor says |url=https://www.wyff4.com/article/south-carolina-schools-will-remain-closed-until-the-end-of-april-governor-says/31916572 |website=WYFF |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The sixth and seventh coronavirus-related deaths are reported by DHEC. One of these was the second death reported from Florence County; this person was reported to have underlying health problems. The other death was reported from Horry County; this person did not have any reported underlying health problems. Additionally, DHEC reported that an individual whose death was originally attributed to Kershaw County actually resided in Sumter County.<ref name=\"deaths67\">{{cite web |title=South Carolina Announces Two Additional Deaths Related to COVID-19 {{!}} SCDHEC |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/index.php/news-releases/south-carolina-announces-two-additional-deaths-related-covid-19 |website=www.scdhec.gov |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 25:''' The death of Jack West, the son of former Governor [[John C. West]], is reported as the eighth in South Carolina and the first from Kershaw County.<ref name=\"death8\">{{cite web |last1=Fretwell |first1=Sammy |title=Coronavirus claims life of lobbyist, son of former South Carolina governor |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/coronavirus/article241397776.html |website=thestate.com |publisher=The State |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 27:'''\n**It is announced that state parks will be closed through the end of April.<ref>{{cite web |title=All SC state parks to close due to COVID-19, park officials say |url=https://www.wyff4.com/article/state-parks-closing-through-april-officials-say/31955615 |website=WYFF |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**President [[Donald Trump]] approves South Carolina's disaster declaration.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pres. Trump approves South Carolina disaster declaration |url=https://www.wbtw.com/news/state-regional-news/pres-trump-approves-south-carolina-disaster-declaration/ |website=WBTW |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''April 1:''' The Governor orders all non-essential businesses closed temporarily.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kalsi |first1=Dal |title=Governor orders 'non-essential' SC businesses in 3 categories to close by 5 p.m. Wednesday |url=https://www.foxcarolina.com/news/governor-orders-non-essential-sc-businesses-in-3-categories-to-close-by-5-p-m/article_1212445a-738d-11ea-af6f-bf7123385b7c.html |website=FOX Carolina |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'''April 3:'''\n**The Governor issues two additional executive orders, one ordering the closure of additional non-essential businesses,<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order No. 2020-18 |url=https://governor.sc.gov/sites/default/files/Documents/Executive-Orders/2020-04-03%20eFILED%20Executive%20Order%20No.%202020-18%20-%20Closure%20of%20Additional%20Non-Essential%20Businesses.pdf |website=South Carolina Office of the Governor}}</ref> and the other enforcing lodging and travel restrictions from people traveling from high-risk areas (New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut).<ref>{{cite web |title=Executive Order No. 2020-19 |url=https://governor.sc.gov/sites/default/files/Documents/Executive-Orders/2020-04-03%20eFILED%20Executive%20Order%20No.%202020-19%20-%20Lodging%20%26%20Travel%20Restrictions%20for%20Individuals%20from%20High-Risk%20Areas.pdf |website=South Carolina Office of the Governor}}</ref>\n**Data of confirmed cases by zip code is first released.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 in South Carolina, by Zip CodesCases as of 4/2/2020 at 11:59 PM |url=https://www.scdhec.gov/sites/default/files/media/document/Covid%20Zip%20Analysis%204_3_2020%20No%20Estimates_0.pdf |website=South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n**DHEC releases data of total persons tested by DHEC Public Health Laboratory and, for the first time, data from private laboratories.<ref name=\"DHECcount\"/>\n\n==Statistics==\n[[File:COVID-19 Cases by counties of South Carolina with scale.png|thumb|right|{{legend|#FFDDCC|1\u20135 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|6\u201310 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|11\u201320 confirmed}}\n{{legend